ine.  \n   - If you draw a line‑chart, you’ll see a dip in February, a sharp peak in March, then a gradual taper back toward the early‑year level by May.\n\n2. **Key highlights:**  \n   - **Peak month:** March 2022 with **142** transactions (≈\u202f11\u202f% above the average).  \n   - **Lowest month:** February 2022 with **115** transactions (≈\u202f9\u202f% below the average).  \n   - **Average (Jan‑May):** ≈\u202f127 transactions per month.  \n\n3. **Potential drivers (speculative):**  \n   - The March surge could reflect a seasonal promotion, a product launch, or an external event that spurred activity.  \n   - The post‑March decline may indicate the promotional effect waning or a return to baseline demand.\n\n### Suggested plot\n- **X‑axis:** Calendar month (Jan\u202f2022\u202f→\u202fMay\u202f2022).  \n- **Y‑axis:** Transaction count.  \n- **Chart type:** Simple line chart (or column/bar chart) with data points labeled for clarity.  \n- **Add a reference line:** Horizontal line at the mean (≈\u202f127) to quickly visualize months above/below average.  \n\n### Quick take‑away\nThe transaction volume has been fairly stable, hovering around 120‑140 per month. The March spike is the most notable deviation, so any further analysis (e.g., correlating marketing spend or external events) should start by investigating what happened that month. If the pattern holds, you can expect future months to oscillate around the 127‑transaction baseline unless a new catalyst emerges.'}}, 'id': 'call_70cd0a7d9537', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[]), ToolMessage(content="Error executing tool: 1 validation error for VisualizationInput\nquery\n  Field required [type=missing, input_value={'tool_input': {'query': ...new catalyst emerges.'}}, input_type=dict]\n    For further information visit https://errors.pydantic.dev/2.12/v/missing", name='error_handler', tool_call_id='error'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, tool_calls=[{'name': 'generate